    - target: {fileID: 3722247126628398497, guid: 3b78f404deb68354e9b08eaf5d093c61,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_text
      value: 'Surface

        radiance'
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 4742801142062538468, guid: 3b78f404deb68354e9b08eaf5d093c61,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_text
      value: 'L<sub>r</sub> = Reflected light from the surface [W / (sr m2)]

        f<sub>r</sub>
        = BRDF light factor = Light reflectance factor given the view and light direction
        [1 / sr]

        E<sub>Surface</sub> = Irradiance of the surface = Amount
        of light hitting the surface [W / m2]


        When light hits the surface,
        two factors are relevant. How much light hits it and how much of it is reflected
        towards the viewer.

        For direct light, the calculation can be a bit
        complex at first, but it can be done well at runtime.

        However, since
        light in reality bounces around the environment, surfaces are not only lit
        by normal lights but also by other reflective surfaces. This cannot be done
        at runtime directly, and different approximations need to be used.'
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5008773921672645143, guid: 3b78f404deb68354e9b08eaf5d093c61,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_Name
      value: Texture filtering
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5054003980637472312, guid: 3b78f404deb68354e9b08eaf5d093c61,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_text
      value: "L<sub>r</sub> = Reflected light from the surface [W / (sr \u22C5 m2)]\r\nf<sub>r</sub>
        = BRDF light factor = Light reflectance factor given the view and light direction
        [1 / sr]\r\nE<sub>Surface</sub> = Irradiance of the surface = Amount of light
        hitting the surface [W / m2]\n\nWhen light hits the surface, two factors
        are relevant. How much light hits it and how much of it is reflected towards
        the viewer.\nFor direct light, the calculation can be a bit complex at first,
        but it can be done well at runtime.\nHowever, since light in reality bounces
        around the environment, surfaces are not only lit by normal lights but also
        by other reflective surfaces. This cannot be done at runtime directly, and
        different approximations need to be used."
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
